
# Week 1

## Day 1 Agile
Agile 

Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC)

agile is a methodology to work through software development 
sequence of steps to get a piece of software to the end user

5-6 stages:
1. requirements gathering (collect client requirements, spec)
2. analysis (breaking requirements down into tasks that need to be completed; assigning tasks to colleagues, design database)
3. designing (software breakdown into modules, classes = architecture, relationships)
4. coding (write the app code)
5. testing (run tests against the code written, manual or automated, validating the code against the requirements)
6. operationalisation (getting the code that the end user can access it; deploy it to the wider audience; maintaining software, feedback from the user, UNTIL the end of life EOL)

all projects go through the above stages

methodology - a way of working through a process

**waterfall vs agile methodologies (can apply to SDLC or other projects)**
**waterfall** - the simplest way, the traditional way, step by step (complete one step and move on to the next) **unidirectional** workflow , never backtracking. waterfall is restrictive as it's not very adaptable (you need to start from scratch when there is a requirement change)
waterfall works for construction, manufacturing due to smaller likelihood that the requirements will change

**agile** - the primary alternative which has been around for a while now. agile aims to be responsive, adaptive and flexible to any changes that may come later. development practices remain more flexible (**iterative** way of working/development), multiple short development cycles and focus on the task on hand. better deliver the software because we're able to work with the client and the changes to the brief; much more collaborative approach by facilitating change and ongoing feedback
agile works for software development, other IT projects and outside of the field where projects can be approached iteratively

problems agile fixes:
- difficulty of the traditional approach (antagonistic?)
- flexibility in terms of making changes
- relationship between client and the team
- quicker delivery
- feedback from the client
- better productivity

there are frameworks to help be more agile but in general it's more of a philosophy e.g. breaking down of requirements into tasks etc.

**agile values** (agile manifesto):
- individuals and interactions over rigid processes and tools (less valuable in being flexible)
- working software over comprehensive documentation (documentation is helpful but build first, the customer wants the software not the documentation)
- customer collaboration over contract negotiation (adapt first and see what impact it has on the contract later)
- responding to change over following a plan (plans are useful but should be open to being changed and change needs to be taken into account)

customer value, proper communication, teamwork/collaboration/passion, feedback, reflection,

### Task. Research XP: 
extreme programming (collaboration, flexibility and continuous improvement)
created in a response to the traditional plan-driven development
close collaboration between developers, customers and stakeholders throughout the development process

XP places a strong emphasis on practices like pair programming, test-driven development, continuous integration, and onsite customer involvement to enable the realization of these values

- short development iterations (entire development cycle)
- dynamic planning (prioritisation based on the most valuable features)
- embrace change
- "pair programming": two programmers work together at a single workstation. One person acts as the "driver," actively writing code, while the other person serves as the "observer" or "navigator," providing real-time feedback, suggestions, and catching errors. Pair programming promotes knowledge sharing, code review, and higher code quality.
- test-driven development (thoroughly testes and verified that it meets desired behaviour)
- frequent integration
- dedicated customer representative 
- sustainable pace

XP, on the other hand, is highly opinionated

XP values:
- simplicity
- communication
- feedback
- courage - encourage individuals to take risks, make difficult decisions and challenge status quo which aligns nicely with communication and people over processes
- respect - promote respectful and supportive work environment, closely to the client so they are heard. it aligns nicely with people over processes as everyone's opinion and contributions should be valued 





## Day 2 SCRUM and Jira

Scrum definitions:
- sprint (1-2 weeks) - development cycle to develop and deliver to client quickly; every sprint will have a goal 
- product increment - produced at the end of each sprint cycle, it should be in a working and stable state; a shippable iteration of the product (features, bugs fixed, some changes)
- minimum viable product MVP - the first sprint should produce the simplest version of the product, the following sprints build on top of that
- product backlog - analysed requirements are added to the product backlog; a live list of requirements
- sprint backlog - subset of product backlog, worked on during sprint 

Scrum is heavy in processes but you don't have to follow all, you can pick and choose

![[Pasted image 20230704093508.png]]

meetings in a SCRUM process:
1. sprint planning meeting ("concrete plan" for the next sprint cycle)
	- deciding on the sprint goal
	- product backlog items that are relevant to build into sprint backlog
	- defining the definition of ready (DOR), acceptance criteria, planning, prioritisation, updating risk assessments
	- involves all core SCRUM team, project manager, (business analyst), no client involvement
2. daily stand up meetings
	- every day throughout the course of the sprint to update the stakeholders & any blockers
	- no more than 10-15 mins 
	- involves project manager and business analyst but for informative purposes, SCRUM master drives the meeting and the rest of SCRUM team will attend
3. sprint review (involves the client)
	- at the end of the sprint, presenting the output (the product increment) of the sprint to the client
	- involves all of the stakeholders including the client
	- client can offer feedback if there is any
	- product owner would be responsible for updating the product backlog
4. sprint retrospective (identifying areas for improvement and strategies to overcome)
	- at the end of the sprint, after the review meeting 
	- involve the SCRUM team
	- analysis of what went well and what needs improvement; develops and communicates strategies for improvement 

stakeholder (have some interest in the project whether it's the client or the dev team):
- development team
- business reps
- client
- external investors

SCRUM roles:
- dev team (**core**)
	- product owner (PO) - responsible for the sprint / product backlogs, keeping the logs up to date with incoming requirements
	- SCRUM master (SM) - facilitating collaboration between team members, chairing daily stand-ups
	- developers - everyone else in the team working on the actual code, devs can focus on the code and backlog is maintained by dedicated team members
- business (separate to the development team) people should work with scrum team on daily basis
	- project manager - responsible for high level strategy & roadmaps, resource management, no micromanagement in scrum, budgeting etc.
	- business analyst - requirements gathering and analysis, client facing activities, client-focused
- client (internal or external) will not work directly with the dev team, more with business analysts



**Product Backlog** - collection of work items (a comprehensive list) required to be completed for product as a whole
all short and medium term requirements 
items:
- **Epics** - **user stories** - individual related **tasks** (hierarchy, higher-level structure, group items together)
- other item types: initiatives, themes, bug fixes/reports

user stories -> expresses a requirement/ a desired feature / a change that needs to be made to the application from the point of view of the end-user:
	as a [persona] I want [change] so that [outcome]
	persona -> stakeholder, the user whether it's a client or 
	change -> a feature, change that the user wants to see
	outcome -> the value proposition for the change; a clear outcome that can be measured after delivery
	user story can be broken down into tasks


![[Pasted image 20230704114004.png]]


epic can spread across multiple sprints

the below definitions will vary depending on the team and project:
- definition of ready (DOR) defines what a product backlog item needs before it can be accepted into the sprint backlog 
	- user stories broken down into tasks
	- estimated work required
	- risk assessment updated
	- acceptance criteria 
- vs definition of done (DOD)  defined what is needed before it can be regarded as complete (consistent definition that applies to the entire backlog)
	- code review
	- tests passed
	- acceptance criteria met
		 acceptance criteria are work item-specific
		 given [precondition] when [event  / action] then [postcondition / testable outcome]
		 derive tests directly from acceptance criteria (validating the code against what the client has asked for)

Jira is a piece of software for agile management - digital project tracking boards

estimation is important for cost estimates and to ensure consistent pace, so we don't end up burnt out or doing too little in a sprint
	- unanimous decisions, so no one feels like they are doing all the work and we have a pretty good idea how long each task will take (fair distribution of work)
	- time is not a good estimate as tasks will vary depending on who works on them; we prefer to measure task complexity 
		story points, unitless, relative measure of complexity - requires some experience
		- planning poker (geometric sequence 2,4,6, etc. to avoid quibbling over single point differences) or 
		- t-shirt sizes (Small - extra-large etc., more intuitive as less experience required)

prioritisation is useful for determining MVP (minimum viable product)
	M - must-have (essential, the app won't function without it) (MVP to include all the Must-haves)
	S - should-have (very beneficial to the user but can be omitted)
	C - could-have (slightly beneficial but can be omitted)
	W - would(won't)-have (not currently planned in the current time-frame)
the alternative is highest-lowest or numerical (numerical is not the best)

risk assessments are used to ensure a project is a success
iterative risk management fits well with Agile methodology with the below steps
- identify the risks 
- assess probability and impact of each to determine severity
- plan proactive and reactive control measures  appropriate to severity determined
- monitor and manage risks throughout the project

some common elements to be included in the risk assessment:
- description of the risk identified
- evaluation - what would happen if the above scenario occurred 
- likelihood / probability 
- impact level - how devastating to the project would it be if this occurred
- responsibility 
- response - what would we do if the scenario occurred
- control measure / mitigation - what can we do to decrease the probability and/or impact

relative vs absolute paths:
- Absolute paths start from the root directory, while relative paths start from the current working directory.
- Absolute paths provide a complete location, while relative paths provide a location relative to the current working directory.
- Absolute paths are the same regardless of the current working directory, while relative paths may change depending on the current working directory.

## Day 4 Linux aliases, user management, data streams

All _variables_, _aliases_ and _functions_ which are defined on the command line will be lost on logout.  
So we need a way to keep these after the user session ends.

There are four files which execute when the user starts a session, these are:

- `/etc/profile` - This is where _variables_ are stored if they need to be set for all users.
- `/etc/bashrc` - This is where _aliases_ and _functions_ are stored if they need to be set for all users.  
    For `ubuntu` machines, the file is called `/etc/bash.bashrc` instead.
- `~/.bashrc` - This is where _aliases_ and _functions_ are stored for one user, this file lives in that user's home directory.
- `~/.profile` - This is where _variables_ are stored for one user, this file lives in that user's home directory.

`du -sk /* 2> /dev/null | sort -n` sorts files by size and throws error in the bin

continuous integration vs continuous delivery/deployment

Continuous Deployment and Continuous Delivery are both practices in software development that aim to automate and streamline the release process, but they differ in the extent to which releases are automated and made available to end users.

Continuous Deployment: Continuous Deployment is a software development practice in which every code change that passes automated tests and quality checks is automatically deployed to production, making it available to end users. The entire release process, including deployment, is fully automated without any manual intervention. Continuous Deployment ensures that the latest version of the software is always deployed, enabling fast and frequent releases.

Continuous Delivery: Continuous Delivery is a software development practice in which software is built, tested, and prepared for deployment in an automated and repeatable manner. However, unlike continuous deployment, the decision to actually deploy the software to production is made manually. Continuous Delivery focuses on maintaining a deployable software release at any given time, with the goal of enabling rapid and reliable release cycles. Once the software is ready for deployment, it can be deployed with minimal effort and risk.

## Day 3 networking and security

### networking 
cisco packet tracer 
a network is a group of two or more devices which are able to communicate

**the why**
- high capacity, networks can transfer large amounts of data
- fast speeds, sending data over a network is usually very fast
- low latency,  the time taken for one packet of data to be transferred between nodes is short
- high availability, networks tend to be reliable, meaning you can send data whenever you want


**layer 0** hardware (physical)
**layer 1** each device will have a predetermined port (address) known as MAC (media access control) address
**layer 2** IP addressing (32-bit number) 4 * 8bits  (router)
	default gateway
ping - is a packet sending thing

physical wire (hub) - cannot have two way traffic; unlike switch will receive both traffic and queue

broadcast domain is **the portion of a network sharing the same layer 2 segment**. Broadcast messages from hosts are sent to every port in their broadcast domain, thus hosts inside a broadcast domain can reach each other directly

### security

data should be secured due to corruption/exfiltration:
- identity theft, the deliberate use of another person's identity
- financial theft, accessing another person's bank account or other financial services
- data ransom, a fear-based form of extortion which aims to convince a victim to part with  or services to prevent the data from being released to the public
- illegitimate sale of data,
- corporate espionage, the act of spying on, or stealing
- reputation loss

CIA -> confidentiality, integrity, availability

risks:
- software threats or technical threats:
	- hacking (data leak, SQL injection)
	- viruses 
	- trojan
	- hardware failure
	- ransomware , spyware, malware
	- denial of service (DOS) (distributed is across many devices, IPs) attack is an attack meant to shut down a machine or network, making it inaccessible to its intended users. DoS attacks accomplish this by flooding the target with traffic, or sending it information that triggers a crash.
		- amplification attack, generate a high volume of packets that are used to overwhelm the target website without alerting the intermediary. This occurs when a vulnerable service responds with a large reply when the attacker sends his request, often called the "trigger packet" (UDP doesn't check the from address and that can be manipulated)
	- man in the middle (mitm) attack infiltrates a connection between 2 hosts and reads the data being transmitted
- social engineering
	- phishing / spear phishing
	- impersonation
	- wateringhole attack, is a targeted attack designed to compromise users within a specific industry or group of users by infecting websites they typically visit and luring them to a malicious site. The end goal is to infect the user's computer with malware and gain access to the organisations network.

authenticating and authorising
- identification (username, password, passport etc)
- authentication is when you can prove you match the identification
	factors:
	- something you know (password)
	- something you have (authenticator app, code, documents) 
	- something you are (biometrics)
	- somewhere you are (geolocation, gps spoofing)
	- something you do (capcha, signature, voice recognition)
- authorisation is what you are authorised to do, which resources you have access to
- auditing is keeping a record of who has authenticated and what authorisation they have
all 4 are required for keeping data secure

protecting passwords:
- hashing algorithms: md6sum, sha512sum
- salting
- encoding
- encrypting (symmetric encryption, asymmetric encryption)
	two keys: one for encryption(public), one for decryption(private)

cloud computing and the cloud have been used to describe all kinds of technology

**cloud computing** is a model for enabling ubiquitous, convenient, on-demand network access to a shared pool of configurable computing resources (eg. networks, servers, storage, applications and services) that can be rapidly provisioned and released with minimal management effort or service provider interaction

---
consumption-based pricing -> a payment scheme where the customer pays according to the amount of resources used (utility model eg. electricity, gas, water)

broad network access -> refers to access to resources over standard network mechanisms (standard protocols such as HTTP or TCP)
	services should be accessible to varying hardware such as phones, laptops, desktops

resource pooling -> cloud services are provided to multiple tenants by a pool of interchangeable resources
	the resources are dynamically assigned and reassigned in order to get optimal use of out of them (storage, processing, memory etc.)
	the resources are location independent - we do not know the exact physical location of the resources

rapid elasticity -> elasticity is a fundamental property of the cloud
	the ability to use exactly the resources you need, without either under-provisioning or excessively over-provisioning
	scale in and out rather than
	**scaling up can be either vertical or horizontal**
	vertical -> means adding or removing the strength of resource capabilities such as RAM or CPU's for the environment
	**horizontal** -> means adding or removing more instances such as a virtual machine or storage area (typical for the cloud) **super important to take scaling out into consideration when building a product/service that will be based on the cloud**
	autoscaling -> scaling in or out automatically based on some defined situations such as traffic levels or utilisation levels


measured service -> it's essential that the customer should be able to monitor the performance and usage of those resources in real-time 

fault tolerance -> the ability for your application to function even if one or more pieces in any layer fails

[shared responsibility model](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/shared-responsibility-model/)

**service models**

***When picking which model to use, think about how much control you might require for the given task.***

The three most common models that will be the focus of these modules are Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS) and Software as a Service (SaaS).

The main differences between the three models can be summed up as follows:

- **IaaS** gives maximum flexibility for hosting custom built applications or acting as a data centre for data storage.
- **PaaS** built on top of IaaS reduces the need for administering the system.  
    Frees up time by not needing to manage infrastructure, time can then be used for development of the application.
- **SaaS** is an out-of-the-box solution that can be readily used. This is built on top of IaaS and PaaS.

### IaaS 
a computing infrastructure that can be provisioned and manager over the internet
IaaS gives maximum flexibility for hosting custom built applications or acting as a data centre for data storage
you pay for what you use
_IaaS_ typically is aimed at developers and those in the Systems field rather than general, non-IT consumers.

advantages:
- **No capital expense and reduction in costs.**: no upfront costs as you pay for what you use. An attractive solution for start-ups.
- **Business continuity and disaster recovery.**: in order to achieve high availability, disaster recovery and business continuity requires a significant investment in both technology and staff. With the right **Service Level Agreement (SLA)** on IaaS you could reduce the costs while achieving the previously mentioned functionality.
- **Rapid innovation**: the infrastructure is ready in minutes or hours for you to launch a product compared to days or weeks when done internally.
- **Rapid response**: can quickly respond to demand with scaling up and down, e.g. to accommodate holiday spikes, and scaling down, which saves money.
- **More focus on business**: time is saved on not requiring to care for the IT infrastructure can be spent on other business needs.
- **Stability, reliability and supportability**: this can be achieved with the right SLA with the provider. Things like software updates, hardware, troubleshooting or equipment problems could be taken care of by the provider freeing up the time to focus on the business.
- **Security**: options provided through the service provider may be better than what you could achieve in-house, though this will depend on the SLA you choose.

### PaaS
an environment in the cloud with all the resources you need for development of cloud-based applications
PaaS is built on top of IaaS, reducing the need for administering the system

it includes all IaaS services with the addition of:
- middleware
- development tools
- business intelligence services
- database management systems

typical use case scenarios:
- development framework
- business intelligence and analytics
- additional services (networking, security, scheduling)

advantages on top of IaaS advantages:
- Improving coding efficiency through the use of in-built tools
- Development options for multiple platforms
- Sophisticated tools for development, business intelligence and analytics through the pay-as-you go model allows for even the smallest companies to utilise them and save time
- Remote teamwork is available, as all the resources are accessible over the internet
- All the capabilities which exist in a typical development environment lifecycle are included - namely building, testing, and deployment

### SaaS
example: Salesforce CRM, Gmail, Office 365
can be described as a readily usable solution built on top of IaaS and PaaS

advantages:
- There is no need to purchase or maintain the SaaS' hardware, software or middleware
- Applications like _ERP_ or _CRM_ become more available, as savings gained from not needing to use in-house software/hardware/middleware can be used for these services instead
- Automatic scaling ensures that, based on your usage, you only ever spend for what you use
- The applications used may not need installing, as the majority of them can be accessed through a web browser
- Mobile device support
- No data loss if the user's personal machine fails, as everything is kept in the cloud and made readily available over the Internet

### public vs private cloud

public cloud is defined as computing services that are available to anyone that wishes to purchase or use them over the internet
- advantages
	- no up-front capital expenditure
	- no maintenance
	- highly reliable
	- easily scalable
- disadvantages
	- less customisable
	- potential latency
	- potential governance issues

we can build our own private cloud in the data centre

private cloud contains computational services which are only available and accessible to select users 
- advantages
	- fully-customisable
	- higher level of security
	- better performance (guaranteed resources (none shared), easy to scale out)
- disadvantages
	- higher upfront capital expense
	- risk of under-utilising resources
	- higher ongoing costs
	- more maintenance required
	the company's IT department will be held responsible for both the cost and the accountability of using a private cloud

hybrid cloud is a combination of the public and private cloud technologies 
	part data centre , part public cloud
	jack-of-all-trades not only do we get all the benefits of the public cloud, but we get those benefits without compromising on security
	this allows to minimise the risk of exposure of sensitive data
- advantages
	- greater flexibility
	- resilience to outages
	- no capacity ceiling
	- manageable security
- disadvantages
	- higher capital expenditure
	- under-utilisation
	- higher ongoing costs
	- more maintenance required
	- risk of compatibility issues

availability zones are independent so as to maintain zone redundancy 

Service Level Agreement (SLA) -> each cloud provider will guarantee a certain percentage of uptime for their VMs

a region id made up of multiple AZ that are interconnected with a low latency network

## Day 1 databases continued

CRUD operations
- create (insert)
- read (select)
- update (update)

database keys -> we want to uniquely identify a record quickly, subsequently associate record from different tables to build relationships

primary key -> is a field in a table that uniquely identifies a record in a table
	it is considered the most important piece of information in the table  (usually given to IDs)
	it is a combination of unique and not null constrains
	a table can only have one primary key

foreign key -> allows us to link tables together we and start creating a relational database
	a field in a table that refers to a primary key in a different table
```CREATE TABLE orders (
order_id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
fk_customer_id INT NOT NULL,
placed DATE NOT NULL,
FOREIGN KEY (fk_customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)
);
```

**data normalisation**
normalisation is the process of modelling the way a database might look by designing its schema
normalisation is needed to reduce the amount of redundant data within the database

database modelling strives to adhere to one of the following paradigms:
- first normal form (1NF)
	- each column should only contain a single value
	- values stored in a column should all be of the same type
	- all columns in a table should have unique names
	- the data should not be stored in any particular order
- second normal form (2NF)
	tables should not contain partial dependencies
	all the information in the table should depend on its primary key
- third normal form (3NF)
	tables should not have any transitive dependencies
	transitive dependency is a non-key dependency


inserting into table
```
INSERT INTO family (family_name) VALUES ("Robinson");

INSERT people (first_name,last_name,age,date_of_birth) VALUES ("Leon",1,21,'2002-10-21')
```

updating the table
```
UPDATE people SET age=48,Date_of_birth='1976-01-01' WHERE first_name="Leon";
```

deleting from the table
```
DELETE FROM people WHERE first_name="Robinson";
```

**aggregate  functions**
a function where the values of multiple rows grouped together to form a single summary value

- count
- sum
- min/max/avg
- group by

## Day 4 Python OOP, classes, files

Object Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts:
- class - a blueprint of attributes and methods which we can use to create objects
- object - an instance of a class
- attribute - data attached to a class or instance of a class
- method - procedures of functions attached to a class

OOP principles:
- Inheritance - One object acquires all the properties and behaviours of a parent object
- Polymorphism (means many forms) - Performing a single action in different ways
- Abstraction - Hiding the implementation details and showing only functionality to the user
- Encapsulation - Wrapping code together and data together into a single unit for data integrity

superclass vs subclass -> we can inherit attributes and methods
superclass -> is the class being inherited from (parent)
subclass -> is the class that is inheriting attributes and methods (child)

**class is built of attributes and methods** 

classes group together attributes and methods which we can reuse many times -> they act as blueprints, allowing us to easily create many different objects of the same type

```Python
class Dog:
	colour = "brown"
	breed = "Labrador"
	personality = "lively"

	def bark():
		pass

	def runabout():
		pass

	 def play():
		pass

fluffy = Dog()
bob = Dog()
spot = Dog()
```

decorator == higher-order function
decorators -> a type of function known as a higher-order function, which is used to extend an existing function with some new functionality

## Day 5 unit testing

testing-> a process of analysing a software item to detect the differences between existing and required conditions and to evaluate the features of the software item
	the cost of fixing defects when a product is in production is far greater than the cost of fixing defects identified in an earlier phase
	releasing buggy code can often have an impact on customer faith and business reputation

different types of testing: 
- functional (does it perform the correct action? - do the code work?)
- non-functional (is the response time acceptable?)
- maintenance (once changes have been made, do all previous tests still pass?)

you should automate testing due to repeatability
	unit testing -> a scripted test in Python to verify unit of functionality
	there are many tools e.g. pytest

```
pytest --cov=factorial.py
pytest factorial_test.py --cov=.

pytest factorial_test.py --cov=applications.factorial --cov-report html
# it then creates a htmlcov folder and index.html will open in a browser


```
